        <mxCell id="HTBFFHoUUt1TWve2A3QG-93" value="&lt;strong&gt;Memory for attention&lt;/strong&gt;: The attention matrix alone would be &lt;code class=&quot;bg-text-200/5 border border-0.5 border-border-300 text-danger-000 whitespace-pre-wrap rounded-[0.4rem] px-1 py-px text-[0.9rem]&quot;&gt;(B, num_heads, 106578, 106578)&lt;/code&gt;. Even with batch size 1 and 12 attention heads, that&#39;s ~136GB just for one layer&#39;s attention weights. You have 16GB total." style="rounded=0;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;align=left;verticalAlign=top;fillColor=#ffe6cc;strokeColor=#d79b00;" parent="1" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry x="376" y="2250" width="332" height="75.5" as="geometry" />
        </mxCell>
        <mxCell id="HTBFFHoUUt1TWve2A3QG-94" value="&lt;h1 style=&quot;margin-top: 0px;&quot;&gt;Brute Force GPT-2&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;div&gt;Converting a GPT-2 into a binary classifier is straightforward, just add a linear layer at the end to change the output size to 1.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The issue is that we are dealing with 100k long token sequences, which results in enormous TransformerBlocks and GPU vRAM memory issues for a measly gaming laptop GPU.&lt;/div&gt;" style="text;html=1;whiteSpace=wrap;overflow=hidden;rounded=0;" parent="1" vertex="1">
          <mxGeometry x="73" y="1660" width="312" height="190" as="geometry" />
